##From "blocking" to "curing" , how Japan's response has fallen behind the epidemic

At the end of January, he hoped Japan would have enough time before the Olympics to fend off new pneumonia.

"We may get more information about the risk of transmission of the virus and the risk of serious illness, so we can also prepare, " the International University of Health and Welfare Public Health Professor told Reuters on Jan. 29, "We can also do some preventive measures to control infection. I hope the Tokyo Olympics will be held as scheduled. "

In 2018, he co-authored a paper examining possible health risks from the influx of tourists to Japan during the 2020 Tokyo Olympics. In the papers of the time, vaccine-preventable diseases such as measles and rubella, as well as food and water-borne diseases, were considered the greatest risks.

These better not-to-be-true "predictions" have not come true, but the greatest risk is a real-life COVID-19 pneumonia (COVID-19) .

On February 16th, exactly a month after Japan confirmed its first case of pneumonia, 12 marathons were held across the country, with tens of thousands of runners. People running in masks during the outbreak and Japan, which will host the Olympics, may be bracing for another "anti-epidemic" marathon.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo: Prime Minister's residence

On the evening of the 16th, the Japanese government Expert Group Meeting did not give the judgment that "Japan is in a period of 'infection' with a rapidly increasing number of patients, " but confirmed that "the infection is in its early stages and will develop further after that. ". As of that date, including the 355 people on the Port of Yokohama Diamond Princess, 413 cases had been confirmed, the highest number of confirmed cases outside of China.

More worrying for the Japanese is the recent confirmation of many cases of "infection path unknown" , unable to track the spread of the virus in Japan.

Japanese Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare Katsunobu Kato said the epidemic "has changed" and that new pneumonia "has actually started to become endemic in Japan" , "From now on, it is necessary to prepare for the prospect of an increase in the number of patients, " she said. "It is a different language from what the government used a month ago. The focus of Japan's response to the epidemic has shifted from port closures to improving its medical system, the Nikkei business daily reported on Feb. 17.

For weeks, the government has been criticized by Japanese experts for "paying attention to border control but not strengthening domestic epidemic prevention" , while the practice of keeping 3,700 people from many countries isolated on cruise ships has been under international pressure.

The World Health Organization (WHO) senior adviser Kuniko Kondo in Yokohama February 14 to attend the Emergency Seminar on New Coronavirus Infectious Diseases simply said: "Now the global concern is Japan. "

###Border Control: Keeping viruses out of the country

Looking only at the cases confirmed in January, only tourists who live in or have visited China, as well as tour guides and drivers who come into contact with tourists, have been infected.

The first case confirmed on January 16 was a Chinese man living in Japan. He had a fever in Wuhan on Jan. 3, returned to Japan on Jan. 6, was hospitalized on Jan. 10, and was discharged a week later. The week after that, there were no new cases in Japan.

The Japanese government said on January 21 that it was "not in the phase of rapid spread of infection" and asked only for information from the entrants. Prime Minister Shinzo Abe said on the 23rd that "every effort will be made to prevent the spread of the epidemic" and called for the strengthening of Control at the ports. Fujiwara Katsumoto said all Chinese passengers arriving in Japan will be strengthened quarantine.

Five more Chinese tourists have been diagnosed in Japan as the Lunar New Year holiday approaches. At this time, Japan also began to launch domestic epidemic prevention measures, on January 28, the new crown pneumonia as a "designated infection" , and then can be imposed on patients with mandatory hospitalization, restrictions on work and other measures.

A day later, the first domestic human-to-human case emerged in the Kansai region area. ŌSAKA confirmed that a bus guide, she and the confirmed 28 Nara Prefecture bus driver on the same bus service tourists from Wuhan.

Confirmed cases have also emerged among the Japanese nationals brought back from Wuhan on a chartered flight by the Japanese government. As of 30 January, five of the passengers on the charter flight were infected, four of whom had no apparent symptoms.

Shinzō Abe had invited Chinese to visit Japan during the holiday and the Olympics in a Chinese New Year message on Jan. 24, but as the epidemic spread, the statement "expect a large number of Chinese tourists to visit Japan" was challenged online, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan later apologised for the "inappropriate" comments and removed them from the website of the Japanese Embassy in Beijing on the 30th.

On January 31, Japan moved up the date of implementation of the "designated infection" regulation from February 7 to February 1, after the WHO declared the outbreak in Wuhan a "public health emergency of international concern. ". On Feb. 1, Japan imposed rare border controls and began to deny entry to foreigners who had stayed in Hubei.

However, as many Chinese tourists have visited Japan during the Spring Festival holiday, and human-to-human transmission of the virus has been confirmed, some scholars doubt the actual effect of the above-mentioned policy and think that we should pay more attention to "treatment" as well as "prevention" .

"We have to know that there have been some cases of infection in Japan, " he told the Asahi Shimbun on Feb. 1, "while a ban on entry would allay some fears, it is hard to say how effective it would be in stopping the domestic spread of the virus. "

He urged the Japanese government to focus on how to prevent a possible infection from developing into a serious illness. "We need to have a medium-to long-term response, " he said. "We need to prevent infection in people at high risk of developing severe symptoms, such as people with underlying diseases and the elderly. ".

###Cruise ship docking: An unsuccessful attempt to isolate

February 1, Japan officially launched the "designated infection" related regulations on the same day, Hong Kong sent a Japan "as if facing the enemy" news. An 80-year-old Hong Kong man who boarded the diamond princess from Yokohama on January 20 and disembarked from Hong Kong five days later was diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia on February 1.

After receiving the notification, the Health Ministry began tracking the patient's close contacts, but a government official said "do not think the case of passing will be infected. ".

However, the rapid development of the epidemic in China makes Japan dare not slacken off. After speeding back to Yokohama, all the people on the cruise took their temperature on Feb. 3, and those with symptoms of cough and fever were tested for the virus.

On February 5th, 10 people on board were confirmed to be infected. From that day on, at the request of the Japanese government, 2,666 passengers and 1,045 crew members on board the ship were forced to be isolated for 14 days, and passengers were not allowed to leave the cabin. "In the face of multiple human infections on large passenger ships, precautions must be taken to prevent proliferation, " Anbe said

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The diamond princess docked in Port of Yokohama

But the outside world does not know whether the ship's protective measures are adequate. As John Lynch, an associate professor of infectious disease at the University of Washington, puts it: "isolation protects those outside, not those inside. "

From 5 February to 16 February, the number of confirmed cases on board the ship surged from 10 to 355, with the infection rate approaching 10 per cent.

The countries of the passengers on board have repeatedly questioned Japan's practice of quarantining cruise ships. "It's a closed environment, it's a ship, it's the perfect place for infectious diseases to spread, " said Rick Rubin, professor of Immunology at Harvard University, this "raises huge questions" .

During the quarantine, a quarantine officer who had worked on board the ship and a government employee who had carried a confirmed case from a cruise ship were also infected. According to the Ministry of Health and Labour investigation, the quarantine officers not only did not wear protective clothing, did not wear goggles, but also repeated the use of face masks, and after wiping the sweat did not properly disinfect the hands.

As the number of cases surged, the pressure-cooker ministry finally announced on February 13th that it would allow some passengers to remain in quarantine at government-arranged accommodation, priority disembarkation passengers are mainly people with underlying diseases and elderly passengers over 80 years old. After February 15, anyone under the age of 80 who tests negative can disembark after February 19, when the quarantine expires, but those in the same room as the infected will remain on board, perhaps until March.

February 15 to 16, the United States, Canada, Hong Kong, China has said it will send chartered flights to pick up the "diamond princess" passengers.

As passengers anxiously awaited the end of the quarantine, it was unclear how many people on board had been infected. As of Feb. 16, only 1,219 people had been tested for the virus, a third of the 3,700 people on board, despite the end of the quarantine period, because of Japan's limited ability to detect it.

###Lack of resources: inadequate preparation

On Feb. 5, the day the ship began its quarantine, Anbe stressed that "safeguarding the lives and health of our citizens is our top priority, " but the main response remains border measures that deny entry to foreigners.

"There are 50 million people in Hubei Province, which is equivalent to refusing entry to half of Japan's population, which is quite extensive at this stage, " he said. On February 13, the ban was extended to foreigners who had stayed in Zhejiang Province.

"My fear is that the government will think that the country is safe if the border is closed, " he told the Japan Times on Feb. 4. "But what the government should do now is to act ahead of time on the assumption that there will be more infections and that the epidemic will continue to worsen in the country, " he said. As of that date, Japan had reported 20 confirmed cases, excluding cruise ships.

Some academics like him worry that the government's focus on averting the virus from China, rather than making a big effort to prepare for an increase in domestic cases, may ultimately prove to be merely "delaying the inevitable" .

"although not as dangerous as SARS, new pneumonia may be more severe than seasonal influenza, " warned National Institute of Infectious Diseases Suzuki, head of Japan's Center for Infectious Diseases, through Kyodo News Agency on Feb. 9, "The possibility that people with mild or no symptoms will have passed through quarantine and have already entered China is not zero, " he said, taking into account the presence of asymptomatic infections among those who flew home from Wuhan on charter flights

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Shop Masks sold out in Japan via Wikicommons

During the outbreak in China, Japanese civilians and local governments donated large amounts of supplies, including masks. Poems such as "the mountains and rivers are foreign, the wind and moon are of the same sky" , "the snow in Liao River melts and the flowers in the mountains bloom; the wind and branches are linked together in anticipation of spring" and "the green mountains are linked together in clouds and rain, and the bright moon has never been the two townships" have aroused heated debate among Chinese netizens.

However, when the secretaries-general of Japan's two ruling parties expressed their willingness to fight the epidemic with all the strength of the country and the Chinese side, the epidemic prevention situation in Japan began to get more and more serious: ordinary shops could not find the traces of masks, flea market APPS also feature a large number of items priced well above the stated price.

Statistics from the Ministry of Health and Welfare show that domestic medical institutions need about 100 million masks a month. About 70 percent of the N95 masks are made overseas, and most of the N95 masks are made in China, which is already in short supply. Japan's domestic mask on the raw materials of China is a lot of the situation, import into the stagnation, the Japanese government has proposed emergency subsidies countermeasures.

How to deal with the shortage of medical resources in the situation of large-scale infectious diseases is also a difficult problem for the government.

"with limited resources, hospitals will always run out of some materials, and if the Tokyo area can handle such a situation, the rest of Japan is not so sure, " he said. "The outbreak is likely to continue for at least a few more months, and the government would be well advised to develop a plan for a long-term response. "

There are only about 1,800 special beds for Infectious Diseases in Japan, Nobuhiko Okabe, director of the health and safety institute in Kawasaki, told the Nikkei on Feb. 12. If patients with mild illnesses also need to be hospitalized, hospitals will soon be full, the mechanism of prioritizing the treatment of critically ill patients is very important.

Nobuhiko Okabe, a former employee of the National Institute of Infectious Diseases, points out that if the epidemic really catches on, specialist clinics alone will be hard to deal with, and small clinics will have to take patients, setting out a route that is separate from the rest of the patients, as is done at large hospitals, and ensuring that hygiene items such as face masks and gloves are in stock, will need to be prepared now.

On February 12, the guidelines for screening patients were revised to only "those who have stayed in Hubei Province of China and their close contacts" . For highly suspected cases, local governments will have the flexibility to test for the virus according to their own judgment, even if they do not meet national testing standards, the ministry said.

The Japanese government is also accelerating the development of new kits to reduce the time it takes to detect the virus from six hours to 30 minutes, with plans to do so by the end of March. In addition, with the assistance of university hospitals and private testing companies, Japan's Daily testing capacity is expected to increase from about 300 to about 1,100 cases.

Jikei University School of Medicine Professor Urashima said February was the first critical period of the Japanese epidemic. In an interview published on February 11 in the Japanese economic news, he said that if there are "infected people who do not know by whom" , it is necessary to be alert to the spread of the virus, reducing large-scale gathering of people can also prevent the spread of the epidemic.

###From blockage to treatment: entering a new stage

The subsequent spread of the disease confirmed that warning.

On February 13, the first fatal case of NCP occurred in a woman in her 80s in Japan. Her son-in-law, a Tokyo taxi driver, was also diagnosed and the route of infection is unknown.

In addition, a male surgeon in his 50s in Wakayama Prefecture has also been infected with the new coronavirus, the first time a doctor has been confirmed in Japan to be infected in the country. He has neither recently traveled overseas nor had contact with anyone from China.

In the following three days, nearly 30 cases were confirmed in Japan, including colleagues attending the New Year's Party with the driver, the venue staff and his family. Five cases were confirmed at the Wakayama Prefecture hospital where the doctor was working, including doctors, doctors'families and hospitalized patients.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare Secretary Katsunobu Kato, Source: NHK

During this period, the medical authorities were unable to account for the history of exposure or possible routes of infection in the first confirmed cases, including in Nagoya, Okinawa, Hokkaido and other locations across the country.

Nobuhiko Okabe said the discovery of human-to-human infections and asymptomatic infections in Japan suggested that the virus was likely to have spread quietly across the country and that the effectiveness of the "aquatic response" -- that is, border control -- had been greatly compromised. The time has come to strengthen domestic responses rather than border controls and to provide prompt treatment once the virus has spread.

He cited Japan's response to the H1N1 influenza epidemic in 2009 as an example. At that time, Japan's border prevention and control measures were counterproductive. If the national expectations for border prevention and control measures were too high, when the epidemic finally broke out, there would be a huge emotional gap, cause a panic.

On 14 February, the day after the first death in Japan, consultation centres located in local health posts received a large number of public consultations. "very worried, hope to be examined" , "can not buy a mask" , "have not been to China, also have no high fever, can go to the hospital to be examined" .

In view of the emergence of patients from all over the country who have no known means of infection, Fujio Katsushiko announced that "the situation has changed from before" , the government's response has also undergone major adjustments, and the domestic epidemic prevention has been strengthened, since 14 February, asymptomatic infected persons have also been placed under mandatory hospital isolation, and the scope for testing for the virus has been expanded. Under the new measure, anyone with suspected pneumonia and other symptoms, regardless of whether they have visited Hubei and Zhejiang areas or have a history of exposure, will be tested.

But a month after the first case emerged, public opinion polls are already judging the government's response.

Kyodo News 15-16, the national telephone opinion survey showed that Anbe cabinet approval rate dropped to 41.0% , "Sakura" under the double pressure of unresolved and the epidemic plunged 8 percentage points from January. As for the impact of the NCP epidemic on the Japanese economy, a total of 82.5% of the public answered "worried" and "somewhat worried" .

An editorial in Japan's Daily News on February 15th said: Previously, "the government's emergency response focused on supporting tourism and other vulnerable sectors and preventing the virus from entering Japan. Now that the country has entered a new phase of infection, the focus should shift to ensuring that Japan is able to cope with a further increase in the number of cases."

"In other words, the government seems to be one step behind and under increasing pressure.
